SIMPLE: fester
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fester
<hw>Fes"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Festered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Festering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>festern</ets>, fr. <ets>fester</ets>, <pos>n.</pos>; <ets>or
fr</ets>. <ets>OF</ets>. <ets>festrir</ets>, fr. <ets>festre</ets>,
<pos>n.</pos> See <er>Fester</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To generate pus; to become imflamed and suppurate; <as>as, a sore
or a wound <ex>festers</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wounds immedicable⟦br⟧
Rankle, and <qex>fester</qex>, and gangrene.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unkindness may give a wound that shall bleed and smart, but it is
treachery that makes it <qex>fester</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hatred . . . <qex>festered</qex> in the hearts of the children of
the soil.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be inflamed; to grow virulent, or malignant; to
grow in intensity; to rankle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fester</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fester
<hw>Fes`ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to fester or
rankle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For which I burnt in inward, swelt'ring hate,⟦br⟧
And <qex>festered</qex> ranking malice in my breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Marston.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fester</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fester
<hw>Fes"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>festre</ets>, L.
<ets>fistula</ets> a sort of ulcer. Cf. <er>Fistula</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A small sore which becomes inflamed and discharges
corrupt matter; a pustule.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A festering or rankling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>fester</qex> of the chain their necks.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Festerment</ent>⟦br⟧
